[39.215898, "o", "\u001b[?2004h\u001b[?25l\u001b[0m\u001b[?7l\u001b[0m\u001b[J\u001b[0;1m[D]iscuss  [E]xecute  [Q]uick  (enter=quick):\u001b[0m\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\u001b[0m \b\u001b[7A\u001b[46C\u001b[?7h\u001b[0m\u001b[?12l\u001b[?25h"]
[39.291826, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[?7l\u001b[0m\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\u001b[0m \u001b[0m\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\u001b[0m \b\u001b[26A\u001b[46C\u001b[?7h\u001b[0m\u001b[?12l\u001b[?25h"]
[48.275817, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[?7l\u001b[46D\u001b[0m\u001b[J\u001b[0;1m[D]iscuss  [E]xecute  [Q]uick  (enter=quick):\u001b[45D\u001b[0m\r\r\n\u001b[J\u001b[?7h\u001b[0m\u001b[?12l\u001b[?25h\u001b[?2004l"]
[56.017574, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36mŌŚå scout\u001b[0m \u001b[2m(Researcher)\u001b[0m\r\nKey differences between `asyncio.gather` and `asyncio.wait`:\r\n\r\n1. **Return value & shape of results**\r\n   - `asyncio.gather(*aws, return_exceptions=False)`  \r\n     - Returns a single *future* whose result is a list/tuple of results in the **same order** as the awaitables you passed in.  \r\n     - If you `await` it: `results = await asyncio.gather(a(), b(), c())` ŌåÆ `results` is `[res_a, res_b, res_c]`.\r\n   - `asyncio.wait(aws, *, return_when=...)`  \r\n     - Returns a pair of **sets**: `(done, pending)`.  \r\n     - You must iterate those futures/tasks yourself and call `.result()` or `.exception()`.\r\n\r\n2. **Error handling behavior**\r\n   - `gather` (default `return_exceptions=False`):  \r\n     - If any awaitable raises, `gather` **propagates** the first exception and **cancels** the remaining tasks.  \r\n     - With `return_exceptions=True`, it collects exceptions as ŌĆ£resultsŌĆØ instead of raising.\r\n   - `wait`:  \r\n     - Does **not** raise itself. You decide how to inspect `.exception()` and what to do with other tasks (cancel, keep running, etc.).\r\n\r\n3. **Completion policy / coordination**\r\n   - `gather`:  \r\n     - Always waits for **all** given awaitables (unless an exception cancels them). No ŌĆ£first-completedŌĆØ mode.\r\n   - `wait(aws, return_when=...)` supports:\r\n     - `FIRST_COMPLETED`\r\n     - `FIRST_EXCEPTION`\r\n     - `ALL_COMPLETED` (the default)  \r\n     This makes it better for races, timeouts, or ŌĆ£wait for anyŌĆØ.\r\n\r\n4. **Typical use cases**\r\n   - Use **`asyncio.gather`** when:\r\n     - You want to run several coroutines in parallel and get their results in order.\r\n     - You want simpler code and ŌĆ£all-or-nothingŌĆØ style error propagation.\r\n   - Use **`asyncio.wait`** when:\r\n     - You care about **partial completion** (e.g., ŌĆ£first response winsŌĆØ).\r\n     - You need fine-grained control over cancellation and error handling.\r\n\r\nWhat kind of scenario are you working with (e.g., ŌĆ£run N HTTP requests and collect them allŌĆØ vs ŌĆ£race multiple tasks and use the first oneŌĆØ)?\r\n\r\n"]
